rdf:Description.rdfs:label: National memorial

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: These are located on lands owned by the government. The Antiquities Act of 1906 authorized the president to declare by public proclamation landmarks, structures, and other objects of historic or scientific interest.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: National monument

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Protected large natural places with significant natural resources, sometimes of significant historic value. Most parks restrict hunting, mining, and similar consumptive activities.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: National or state park

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: A parkway is a roadway in combination with adjacent parkland paralleling the roadway that often connects cultural or historic sites. The primary activity here is scenic motoring along a protected corridor.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: National parkway

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Similar to national parks in purposes and activities except that Congress has permitted other activities, such as hunting, trapping, extraction, and oil and gas exploration. Currently, many preserves would qualify as national parks if not for sport hunting.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: National preserve

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Most of them (12 by last count) are located around large reservoirs and emphasize water-based recreational activities. Some (five by last count) are near major population centers; they focus on preserving scarce open space and historic resources for easy access to large numbers of people.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: National recreation area

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: This category includes other designations, such as national river and recreation area, national scenic river, wild river, etc. Although the first established National River was in 1964, many others were added to this designation following the Wild and Scenic Rivers Act of 1968.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: National river

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Located on the Atlantic, Gulf, and Pacific coasts, the National Park Service maintains 10 of these--some with facilities, many remain in natural state. They allow hunting on many of these sites.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: National seashore

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: These are linear parklands and sometimes referred to as national scenic trails and national historic trails. The National Trails System Act of 1968 authorized more than 3,600 miles of such trails.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: National trail

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Use this classification for all parks without special economic functions. The other LBCS dimensions should be applied to code the type of park. Use the ownership dimension to distinguish between public and private parks, the site dimension to distinguish between community parks and state parks, etc.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Natural and other recreational parks

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Natural environment parks protect the landscapes and special features of the natural region in which they are located. Some provide for limited activities, such as swimming and camping.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Natural environment parks

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Natural resources-related activities

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Nature reserve parks protect natural habitats including significant land forms. Public access in most reserves is restricted because of concerns for the fragile nature of the habitats protected. Most allow research and educational activities.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Nature reserve

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Communications station

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Naval facility

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Naval installation

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Reserve station

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Supply center

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Often used with access to light where the servient tenement is prohibited from blocking or interrupting light or air.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Negative easement

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Usually configured as a straight-line strip with no enclosed walkway or mall area; sometimes a canopy may connect the storefronts. Sizes vary from 30,000 to 150,000 square feet on sites ranging from 3 to 15 acres, and have a 3-mile primary trade area radius. Typically serves immediate neighborhood with convenience shopping. Often anchored by a supermarket or a drugstore, the center offers groceries, drugs, sundries, snacks, and personal services. Track the establishments in this type of structure by applying the appropriate code(s) from the function dimension.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Neighborhood center (convenience with one or more anchors)

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Neighborhood or local park

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: This class comprises establishments supplying information, such as news reports, articles, pictures, and features, to the news media.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: News syndicate

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Nine units

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: When using a three-level coding scheme, apply this category to mean "between ten and twenty units."
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Nineteen units

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Ninety-eight units

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Ninety-five units

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Ninety-four units

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Ninety-nine units and more

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Ninety-one units

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Ninety-seven units

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Ninety-six units

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Ninety-three units

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Ninety-two units

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: When using a three-level coding scheme, apply this category to mean "more than eighty units."
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Ninety units

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Most private property falls into this category. Some private property may, however, have additional legal constraints to ownership. For some planning applications, tracking such constraints may be useful in determining the limits of the use of the property.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: No constraints--private ownership

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: May also be used as a placeholder for areas of no habitation (desert areas, for example).
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: No human activity or unclassifiable activity

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: No structure

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: These establishments provide local or long-distance trucking of non-used goods using specialized equipment, such as flatbeds, tankers, or refrigerated trailers.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Freight trucking, specialized (except used goods)

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Establishments in the nondurable goods subcategory sell or arrange the purchase or sale of nondurable goods to other businesses. These establishments wholesale products, such as paper products, chemicals, drugs, textiles, apparel, footwear, groceries, farm products, petroleum products, alcoholic beverages, books, magazines, newspapers, flowers, and tobacco products. Nondurable goods generally have a life expectancy of less than three years.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Nondurable goods

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Establishments in this subcategory transform, mine, and quarry nonmetallic minerals, such as sand, gravel, stone, clay, and refractory materials. Included are establishments that manufacture bricks, refractories, ceramics, glass, cement, concrete, lime, gypsum, abrasives, ceramic plumbing fixtures, statuary, cut stone products, and mineral wool. Processes used include grinding, mixing, cutting, shaping, and honing. Mining, beneficiating, and manufacturing often occur at a single location. Establishments that mine, quarry, or beneficiate, and then further process, are classified by their primary activity. For example, a mine that manufactures a more-finished product is classified here, while a mine that mines and beneficates with little manufacturing of finished products, is classified under Mining.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Nonmetallic mineral products

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: This category comprises establishments that mine, quarry, or develop the mine site for dimension stone (i.e., rough blocks and slabs of stone) or limestone (including related rocks, such as dolomite, cement rock, marl, travertine, and calcareous tufa). Included in this category are preparation plants that beneficiate limestone (e.g., by grinding or pulverizing).
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Nonmetallic mining

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Nonprofit educational

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Nonprofit other

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: This category corresponds to assessors' categories for nontaxable entities. These may vary widely between jurisdictions, but the subcategories reflect the most commonly used classes.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Nonprofit ownership restrictions

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Nonprofit philanthropic

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Nonprofit religious

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Use this code as a permanent code for those records that will never be classified in this dimension. It is normal for land-use databases to have records that may never be classified and be left blank instead. But LBCS recommends that all records have a code because some computer applications may not be able handle blank entries (null values in database terminology).
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Not applicable to this dimension

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Use this code as a permanent code for those records that will never be classified in this dimension. It is common for land-use databases to have records that are never classified, but left blank instead. However, LBCS recommends that all records have a code because some computer applications may not be able handle blank entries (null values in database terminology).
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Not applicable to this dimension

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Use this code as a permanent code for those records that will never be classified in this dimension. It is normal for land-use databases to have records that may never be classified and left blank instead. But LBCS recommends that all records have a code because some computer applications may not be able handle blank entries (null values in database terminology).
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Not applicable to this dimension

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Use this code as a permanent code for those records that will never be classified in this dimension. It is normal for land-use databases to have records that may never be classified and left blank instead. But LBCS recommends that all records have a code because some computer applications may not be able handle blank entries (null values in database terminology).
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Not applicable to this dimension

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Use this code as a permanent code for those records that will never be classified in this dimension. It is normal for land-use databases to have records that may never be classified and left blank instead. But LBCS recommends that all records have a code because some computer applications may not be able handle blank entries (null values in database terminology).
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Not applicable to this dimension

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: This comprises establishments operating nuclear electric power generation facilities. These facilities use nuclear power to produce electric energy. Electric energy produced in these establishments is provided to electric power transmission systems or to electric power distribution systems.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Nuclear

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Nursery and preschool

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Establishments in this class grow nursery products, nursery stock, shrubbery, bulbs, fruit stock, sod, and so forth; or, grow short rotation woody trees with a growth and harvest cycle of 10 years or less for pulp or tree stock. Establishments growing trees on production cycles over 10 years are classified in "forestry and logging".
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Nursery and tree production

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Typical office uses should be categorized here including those that are primarily office-use in character. Use this category as a catch-all designation for all office-type uses.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Office activities

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Typically associated with drive-through windows at banks, department of motor vehicles, and other businesses. Traditionally, these activities were associated with banks, post offices, and financial institutions, but they may also occur at other kinds of establishments.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Office activities with high turnover of automobiles

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Especially those that have counters for customer service, or waiting areas for customers or visitors. Use this category to indicate an activity characterized by a steady stream of people when such activity is part of normal operations of the office use.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Office activities with high turnover of people

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: These establishments: a). provide day-to-day office administrative services, such as financial planning, billing, record keeping, personnel employment, and logistics; b). hold securities (or other equity interests) of companies in order to own a controlling interest or influence management decisions; c). oversee and administer the establishments of a company often by providing strategic or organizational planning; and d). provide other administrative services not classified elsewhere. Only use this classification for stand-alone establishments which, although they may be part of a larger companies, are separate from the actual goods or services producing facilities. The activities of these establishments could apply equally to a manufacturing company, a law firm, etc.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Office and administrative services

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: This is a catch-all category to differentiate office buildings with street-level retail uses from a purely office building. Structurally, they are similar to a regular office building but vary in their treatment of street-level portion of the structure. Track the establishments in this type of structure by applying the appropriate code(s) from the function dimension.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Office building over storefronts

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: An office building with drive-in windows to serve customers in automobiles.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Office building with drive-through facility

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Buildings constructed for office-type uses. Typically these buildings constitute the majority of nonresidential structures in a community.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Office or bank building

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Use this category for areas that the land-use database is not recording as multiple uses in a structure. Structurally, they may have some unique characteristics. Many planning applications in older neighborhoods can apply this category for large portions of their inventory.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Office or store building with residence on top

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Office supply manufacturing establishments manufacture office supplies with the exception of paper. Examples of products made by these establishments are pens, pencils, felt tip markers, crayons, chalk, pencil sharpeners, staplers, hand operated stamps, modeling clay, and inked ribbons.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Office supplies, inks, etc.

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Establishments in this category operate and develop oil and gas field properties. Activities include exploration for crude petroleum and natural gas; drilling, completing, and equipping wells; operation of separators, emulsion breakers, desilting equipment, and field gathering lines; and all other activities in the preparation of oil and gas until shipment. This category includes establishments that produce crude petroleum, that mine and extract oil from shale, that produce natural gas, and that recover hydrocarbon liquids from oil and gas field gases. Establishments may operate on their own account or for others on a contract or fee basis.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Oil and natural gas

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Because these structures are of special concern for emergency management and other disaster recovery applications, they appear in a separate category with subcategories useful for emergency planners. Many state and federal emergency management applications (as described in the U.S. Federal Emergency Management Agency's HAZUS manual) specify these distinctions.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Oil refinery facility

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: On-ground anchored concrete tank

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: On-ground anchored steel tank

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: On-ground unanchored concrete tank

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: On-ground unanchored steel tank

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: On-ground wood tank

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Many newer industrial structures may look and generate impacts like a typical office building, but they rely on special power, water, or waste disposal systems for operations.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: One-story modern manufacturing plants

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: This comprises Internet access providers, Internet service providers, and similar establishments providing direct access through telecommunications networks to computer-held information compiled or published by others.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Online information services

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Surface parking, open

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Optical establishments retail prescription or nonprescription eyeglasses and contact lenses. This category also includes establishments that provide customer fitting or lens grinding in addition to eyeglasses.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Optical

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Activities primarily associated with storing and moving of military ordnance.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Ordnance storage

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Use this classification for specialized air transportation. Most of these establishments operate for scenic or sightseeing purposes. Examples of transportation types include: hot air balloon rides, helicopter rides, and aerial tram and cable cars.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Other air transportation (including scenic, balloon, etc.)

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: This is a catch-all category for all other mass assembly structures, including community halls, reception halls, wedding halls, etc.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Other community structures

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Other easements

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Hotline centers, suicide crisis centers, self-help organizations, etc., are some examples of establishments in this class.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Other family services

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Farm-related structures include barns and others, such as: ash house, a farm building to store ash or fertilizers; backhouse, a brewing house attached to a farm or farming structure; bark house, a farm building to store barks of trees; hay barns and chaff houses for storing hay and animal feed; boiling house, a structure where animal feed is prepared; chitting house, a shed to germinate and grow potatoes; laithe, a cow-house with crop storage space; hemmel, a shelter for farm animals with no stalls; etc.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Other farm and farming-related structures

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Use this category for government-owned establishments not classified elsewhere.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Other government functions

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Include all other instructional activities here.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Other instructional activities including those that occur in libraries

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Other irrigation facilities

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: These categories are mainly for those applications that may want further differentiation. Track the establishments in this type of structure by applying the appropriate code(s) from the function dimension.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Other kinds of shopping centers

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Other miscellaneous structures

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Other nonclassified road

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Other principal arterial

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Other special purpose parks

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: For tracking the number of occupants, guest rooms, or beds, use additional attributes or fields in the land-use database.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Other specialized residential structures

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: This is a catch-all category for all other residential structure types that do not easily classify in any of the other residential categories. For tracking the number of occupants, guest rooms, or beds, use additional attributes or fields in the land-use database.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Other structurally converted buildings

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Use this category for classifying outdoor storage areas, such as those used for dumping, container stacking, lumber stacks, etc. These include areas that may or may not be graded.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Outdoor storage areas, graded or ungraded

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Strip configuration is the most common format, but others include malls and "village cluster." Many also have outdoor sales areas. Sizes vary from 50,000 to 400,000 square feet on sites ranging from 10 to 50 acres (some may be as big an 100 acres), and have a 25- to 75-mile primary trade area radius. Contains mostly manufacturers' outlet stores selling their own products at discounts. They are commonly found in rural areas and sometimes near tourist locations. Typically there is no anchor, but some stores may be larger than a typical anchor store and function like one to draw customers. Track the establishments in this type of structure by applying the appropriate code(s) from the function dimension.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Outlet or discount center (manufacturer outlet stores)

rdf:Description.dc:source: Land-Based Classification Standards American Planning Association http://www.planning.org/lbcs
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Use this code as a placeholder until an appropriate code can be assigned. It is normal for land-use databases to have records that may never be classified and left blank instead. But LBCS recommends that all records have a code because some computer applications may not be able handle blank entries (null values in database terminology). This code could also be used as the default value for data-entry work. The subcategories serve the same purpose for other coding levels.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: To be determined
